From John S Neff Subject Re Space spinn offs In article rruis do bigboote WPI EDU wfbrown wpi WPI EDU William F Brown writes From wfbrown wpi WPI EDU William F Brown Subject Re Space spinn offs Date Apr GMT I just wanted to point out, that Teflon wasn't from the space program It was from the WWII nuclear weapons development program Pipes in the system for fractioning and enriching uranium had to be lined with it Uranium Hexafloride was the chemical they turned the pitchblend into for enrichment It is massively corrosive Even to Stainless steels Hence the need for a very inert substaance to line the pipes with Teflon has all its molecular sockets bound up already, so it is very unreactive My sense worth Bill The artifical pacemaker was invented in by Wilson Greatbatch an American biomedical engineer The bill authorizing NASA was signed in October of so it is clear that NASA had nothing to do with the invention of the pacemaker